      "content": "The criticism is overwhelmingly directed at the UN's structural design, specifically the Security Council's veto power which institutionalizes great power self-interest and paralyzes action when consensus is impossible. While member states certainly limit the organization's reach, historians argue this isn't a mere political limitation but a fundamental flaw that makes the UN incapable of enforcing peace against determined aggressors. The system was built to prevent World War III, not to actively stop genocides or wars in the 21st century, and its failure to do so is a direct result of its own architecture rather than just temporary political hurdles.",
